    think='Let me now check some more critical things:\n1. Check if matching.mod
ule.ts imports ImModule (PR body says it was updated, but I saw it doesn\'t)\n2.
Check the design system components\n3. Check the BDD setup for IM\n4. Check if t
here are issues with snowflake vs bigserial\n5. Check the next_cursor calculatio
n in getMessages - it returns messages[0].sequence_id but messages were reversed
, so it returns the oldest sequence_id in the page, not the newest. This seems l
ike a bug.\n\nWait, let me re-read getMessages:\n```typescript\nconst results = 
await qb.getMany();\nconst hasMore = results.length > parsedLimit;\nconst messag
es = hasMore ? results.slice(0, parsedLimit) : results;\n// Return in ascending 
order for display\nmessages.reverse();\nconst nextCursor = hasMore && messages.l
ength > 0 ? String(messages[0].sequence_id) : null;\n```\n\nAfter `messages.reve
rse()`, `messages[0]` is the oldest message in the page (since original was DESC
, slice took the first `parsedLimit` which are the newest, then reverse makes ol
dest first). So `nextCursor` = oldest sequence_id. But for pagination to work co
rrectly, the cursor should be the boundary after which older messages are fetche
d. If the client passes `cursor=oldest_sequence_id`, the query does `sequence_id
< cursor`, which would exclude the current page and get older messages. That act
ually seems correct for "load more older messages".\n\nWait, let me think again:
\n- Query orders by `sequence_id DESC`\n- Gets newest first\n- `cursor` means "g
et messages with sequence_id < cursor" (older than cursor)\n- First page: gets m
essages [100, 99, 98, ... 81] (newest 20)\n- hasMore=true, messages = [100, 99, 
... 81], then reverse = [81, 82, ... 100]\n- nextCursor = 81\n- Second page with
cursor=81: gets messages with sequence_id < 81, i.e., [80, 79, ... 61]\n- This i
s correct!\n\nActually wait, no. If `messages.reverse()` turns `[100,99,...,81]`
into `[81,82,...,100]`, then `messages[0]` is `81`. The next query uses `cursor 
< 81` to get older messages. This is correct.\n\nBut there\'s another issue: `qb
.take(parsedLimit + 1)` then `hasMore ? results.slice(0, parsedLimit) : results`
. The `take` in TypeORM with `getMany()` actually limits the SQL result to `pars
edLimit + 1`. If `hasMore=true`, we slice to `parsedLimit`. Then we reverse. Thi
s is correct.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at getConversations:\n```types
cript\nconst nextCursor = hasMore && pageParticipants.length > 0\n  ? pagePartic
ipants[pageParticipants.length - 1].updated_at.toISOString()\n  : null;\n```\n\n
`pageParticipants` is ordered by `c.updated_at DESC`. So `pageParticipants[0]` h
as the newest updated_at, and `[length-1]` has the oldest. So `nextCursor` is th
e oldest updated_at in the page. The next query uses `cursor: new Date(cursor)` 
with `c.updated_at < :cursor`. This would correctly get conversations older than
the last one. Correct.\n\nNow let me check for potential issues:\n\n1. **Matchin
gModule does NOT import ImModule** - The PR body says it was updated to import I
mModule, but in the file I read, matching.module.ts does NOT import ImModule. Ho
wever, matching.service.ts uses `EventEmitter2` to emit `match:created`, and ImS
ervice has `@OnEvent("match:created")`. This works through the global EventEmitt
erModule, so ImModule doesn\'t need to be imported by MatchingModule. But the PR
body explicitly says "更新 matching.module.ts - 引入 ImModule". This is a discre
pancy - either the PR body is wrong or the file wasn\'t updated as claimed.\n\nW
ait, let me re-check matching.module.ts from the diff. The PR diff might have ch
anged it but I read the current state. Let me check if matching.module.ts was ac
tually changed.\n\n2. **BDD step definitions** - They seem to have actual implem
entations, not empty.\n\n3. **Snowflake vs bigserial** - PRD says `sequence_id` 
should use database auto-increment `bigserial`. The migration uses `sequence_id 
BIGINT NOT NULL` (not auto-increment), and the code uses `Snowflake.nextId()`. T
his is inconsistent with the PRD. The PRD specifically says "sequence_id 使用数
据库自增 bigserial". This is a functional deviation from the PRD.\n\n4. **Missin
g `make test` check** - PR body checklist shows `[ ] make test` is unchecked (tr
uncated but the `[ ]` is visible). According to the template, `make test` is req
uired.\n\n5. **Widgetbook registration** - I need to check if the new components
are registered in widgetbook.\n\n6. **Golden files** - They exist: `apps/mobile/
test/goldens/sw_chat_bubble_variants.png` etc. Good.\n\n7. **Accessibility in Ch
atPage** - The `SwChatInputBar` is used without an identifier. I need to check i
f it has one.\n\n8. **ImBloc close()** - `close()` disposes the socket, but `ImB
loc` is a lazy singleton. If the app calls `close()` somehow, it could be proble
matic, but normally BlocProvider doesn\'t call close on lazy singletons... Actua
lly, `BlocProvider` DOES call `close()` when the widget is disposed. But `ImBloc
` is registered at the `MaterialApp.router` level via `MultiBlocProvider` in `So
cialWorldApp`, which is a `StatelessWidget`. When would it be disposed? Only whe
n the app is destroyed. So this is fine.\n\nWait, actually `BlocProvider(create:
(_) => getIt<ImBloc>())` - if `create` returns an existing instance from getIt, 
BlocProvider will still call `close()` on it when disposed. But since the app-le
vel provider is never disposed during normal operation, this is fine.\n\n9. **So
cket connection timing** - In `app.dart`, `ImConnectRequested` is dispatched whe
n `AuthAuthenticated` is detected. But `BlocListener` might fire after the initi
al build. This seems okay.\n\n10. **Design system hardcoded colors** - I should 
check the components.\n\nLet me now check some remaining critical items:\n- widg
etbook/main.dart\n- design system components\n- matching.service.ts tests\n- BDD
setup for IM\n- Check if matching.module.ts was actually changed in the diff',
