ns the developer explicitly did NOT run or did NOT pass `make test`. According t
o the template, this is a required checklist item. Since it\'s unchecked, this i
s a Major issue.\n\nNow let me check if there\'s any other critical issue I migh
t have missed:\n\n1. **OpenAPI contract inconsistency**:\n   - `MessageDto` stat
us enum: `[sent, read]` but actual code uses `sent`, `delivered`, `read`, `sendi
ng`, `failed`. The DTO only returns backend status, which can be `sent` or `read
` (the DB default is `sent`). But in `im.service.ts`, `markAsRead` doesn\'t upda
te `message.status` to `read` - it only updates `participant.last_read_message_i
d`. The `message.status` field in DB doesn\'t track read state per participant; 
read state is tracked via `last_read_message_id` in the participant table. So `m
essage.status` in DB is always `sent` unless explicitly changed. The OpenAPI say
s enum `[sent, read]` which might be okay if the backend only returns these two 
values. But actually, `im.service.ts` never updates `message.status` to `read`. 
The read status is tracked via `last_read_message_id` on the participant.\n\nWai
t, looking at the PRD:\n> 消息状态应该 progress from "sending" to "sent" to "del
ivered"\n\nAnd:\n> Mobile 侧根据 `last_read_message_id` 和消息 `sequence_id` 决
定哪些消息显示「已读」状态。\n\nSo `message.status` in the DB represents the del
ivery status (`sent`, `delivered`), while `read` is computed client-side based o
n `last_read_message_id`. But the OpenAPI contract says `enum: [sent, read]`. Th
is is inconsistent with the actual backend DTO which returns `status: "sent"` fo
r all persisted messages. The backend never sets `status: "read"` on messages.\n
